[[File:All Saints Church, Whitefield.jpg|thumb|West end of All Saints]]

'''All Saints' Church, Whitefield''', is located in Church Lane, [[Stand, Greater Manchester|Stand]], [[Whitefield, Greater Manchester|Whitefield]], [[Greater Manchester]], England.  It is an active [[Anglicanism|Anglican]] [[parish church]] in the deanery of Radcliffe and Prestwich, the archdeaconry of Bolton, and the [[Anglican Diocese of Manchester|diocese of Manchester]].<ref>{{Citation | url = http://www.achurchnearyou.com/stand-all-saints/| title = All Saints, Stand, Whitefield| accessdate = 15&nbsp;December 2011| publisher = [[Church of England]]}}</ref>  The church has been designated by [[English Heritage]] as a Grade&nbsp;I [[listed building]].<ref name=nhl>{{NHLE |num= 1356818|desc= Church of All Saints, Bury|accessdate= 15&nbsp;December 2011}}</ref>  It was a [[Commissioners' church]], having received a grant towards its construction from the Church Building Commission.<ref name=port>{{Citation | last = Port| first = M. H.| author-link = | publication-date = | date = | year = 2006| title = 600 New Churches: The Church Building Commission 1818-1856 | edition = 2nd| volume = | series = | publication-place = Reading| place = | publisher = Spire Books| pages = | page = 327| id = | isbn = 978-1-904965-08-4| doi = | oclc = | url = | accessdate =}}</ref>  The church is a tall building, standing on high ground, and is constructed on a platform.<ref name=pev/>

==History==

The church was built between 1821 and 1826.  The architect [[John Soane|Sir&nbsp;John Soane]] was invited to design the church to accommodate about 1,800&nbsp;people, and to cost no more than <U+00A3>12,000.  He declined and passed the commission to [[Charles Barry]].<ref name=hist1>{{Citation | url = http://www.allsaintsmanchester.org/history1819-25.htm| title = History 1819<U+2013>25| accessdate = 15&nbsp;December 2011| publisher = Parish Church of All Saints, Stand}}</ref>  This church was Barry's first commission.<ref name=pev/><ref name=nhl/>  Its design was similar to his design for St Matthew, Campfield. [[Manchester]] (which has since been demolished).<ref name=pev>{{Citation | last =Hartwell | first =Clare | authorlink = | last2 = Hyde | first2 = Matthew | author2-link =| last3 = Pevsner | first3 = Nikolaus | author3-link = Nikolaus Pevsner | series= The Buildings of England| title =Lancashire: Manchester and the South-East |edition= | publisher =[[Yale University Press]] | year =2004 | location =New Haven and London | pages = 678<U+2013>679| url = | doi = | id = | isbn =0-300-10583-5 }}</ref>  A grant of <U+00A3>13,812 (<U+00A3>{{formatnum:{{Inflation|UK|13812|1826|{{CURRENTYEAR}}|r=-4}}}} as of {{CURRENTYEAR}}){{Inflation-fn|UK}} was given towards its construction by the Church Building Commission.<ref name=port/>{{ref label|Location|A|A}}  The foundation stone was laid on 3&nbsp;August 1821, and the church was [[consecration|consecrated]] by the [[Bishop of Chester]] on 8&nbsp;September 1826.<ref name=hist1/>

==Architecture==
===Exterior===
All Saints is constructed in [[millstone grit]] from the [[Pennines]].<ref name=hist2>{{Citation | url = http://www.allsaintsmanchester.org/history%201826%20on.htm| title = History 1826 on| accessdate = 15&nbsp;December 2011| publisher = Parish Church of All Saints, Stand}}</ref>  The architectural style is described as "fanciful" [[English Gothic architecture|Gothic]].<ref name=pev/><ref name=nhl/>{{ref label|Location|B|B}}  The plan of the church is rectangular in five [[bay (architecture)|bays]], with a [[Cant (architecture)|canted]] [[apse]] at the east end, and a west porch and tower.  The lowest stage of the tower forms the porch, which is entered through tall narrow pointed arches.  The bell openings are pairs of [[lancet window|lancet]]s.  Along the sides of the church are two tiers of windows.  The tower and the body of the church have [[battlement|embattled]] [[parapet]]s and [[crocket]]ed [[pinnacle]]s.<ref name=nhl/>

===Interior===
Inside the church are galleries on three sides carried on slender [[English Gothic architecture#Perpendicular Gothic|Perpendicular]] [[pier (architecture)|piers]].  The plaster ceilings are [[vault (architecture)|vaulted]].  The altar, screen and [[pulpit]] date from 1921, the choir stalls and side screens date from 1937; all of these were designed by the [[Lancaster, Lancashire|Lancaster]] architects [[Sharpe, Paley and Austin#Austin and Paley (1925<U+2013>1944)|Austin and Paley]].  The stained glass in the east window dates from 1841 and is by D.&nbsp;Evans of [[Shrewsbury]].  Elsewhere are windows by [[Lavers, Barraud and Westlake]], and by [[A. L. Moore|A.&nbsp;L.&nbsp;Moore]], the latter dating from 1921.  The monuments include one by [[Robert William Sievier|Sievier]] dating from 1826 depicting a lady lying on a ''[[chaise longue]]''.<ref name=pev/>  The original organ was built by [[Samuel Renn]] in 1827 and situated in the west gallery.  It was moved in 1880 to the north aisle.  This organ was removed from the church in 1957.<ref name=hist2/>  It was replaced by the present three [[manual (music)|manual]] organ made by Charles A.&nbsp;Smethurst.  This organ was rebuilt in 1997 by Nicholson of [[Worcester]].<ref>{{Citation | url = http://www.npor.org.uk/cgi-bin/Rsearch.cgi?Fn=Rsearch&rec_index=R00073| title = Lancashire (Manchester, Greater), Stand, All Saints (R00073)| accessdate = 15&nbsp;December 2011| publisher = [[British Institute of Organ Studies]]}}</ref>  The [[ring of bells|ring]] consists of eight bells, all of which were cast in 1912 by [[Gillett & Johnston|Gillett and Johnston]].<ref>{{Citation | url = http://dove.cccbr.org.uk/detail.php?searchString=whitefield&Submit=+Go+&DoveID=STAND| title = Stand, Whitefield, All Saints| accessdate = 15&nbsp;December 2011| publisher = [[Dove's Guide for Church Bell Ringers]]}}</ref>

